getPropertyInScope 
 public ESValue getPropertyInScope(String propertyName,
                                   ScopeChain previousScope,
                                   int hash) throws EcmaScriptException
Either return the property value of the specified property in the current object, or lookup the next object in the scope chain if there is one. If there is nones, generate an error message.

This routine must be overriden by subclass which change the implementation of getProperty.

Parameters:
propertyName - The property to look for
previousScope - The previous scope or null
hash - The hashCode of propertyName
Returns:
The value of the specified variable
Throws: EcmaScriptException
if not found in any scope

getProperty 
 public ESValue getProperty(int index) throws EcmaScriptException
Get the property by index value. By default the index is converted to a string, but this can be optimized for arrays.

This is not the same as the indexed properties of the first version of JavaScript and does not allow to access named properties other than the property using the integer string representation as a name.

Parameters:
index - The property name as an integer.
Returns:
The property or undefined
Throws: EcmaScriptException
Error in host objects ?

deleteProperty 
 public boolean deleteProperty(String propertyName,
                               int hash) throws EcmaScriptException
Implements the [[delete]] function (8.6.2.5), only called by the DELETE operator. Should return true if the propery does not exist any more (or did not exist at all) after the return.

This routine must implement the DontDelete attribue too.

doIndirectCall 
 public ESValue doIndirectCall(Evaluator evaluator,
                               ESObject target,
                               String functionName,
                               ESValue arguments[]) throws EcmaScriptException, NoSuchMethodException
A construct as thisObject.functionName() was detected, The functionName is looked up, then a call is made. This avoid creating a dummy function object when one does not exists, like for the ESWrapper objects (where functions are really java methods).

Only method which do not use the standard EcmaScript function evaluation mechanism need to override this method.

Parameters:
evaluator - The evaluator
target - The original target (for recursive calls)
functionName - The name of the function property
arguments - The arguments of the function
Returns:
The result of calling the function
Throws: EcmaScriptException
Function not defined
Throws: NoSuchMethodException
Method not found
